===========================================================================

Customizations:  see ~/wisdom/setup/setup-preferences

===========================================================================

On Windows:
 * close VMware workstation & other programs first
 * don't make OpenOffice the default, because it will change the
   icons for programs and when you make Office the default again, they won't
   change back.  [As of 3.2, it didn't seem to ask to make itself the default.]

===========================================================================

On Debian, edit /etc/openoffice/sofficerc, changing Logo=1 to Logo=0.

===========================================================================

Ubuntu:

sudo apt install libreoffice

===========================================================================

OpenOffice 3.0.0 for Linux

mkdir -p /scratch/mernst/oo-install
cd /scratch/mernst/oo-install
wget http://openoffice.cs.utah.edu/stable/3.0.0/OOo_3.0.0_LinuxIntel_install_wJRE_en-US.tar.gz
tar xzf OOo_3.0.0_LinuxIntel_install_wJRE_en-US.tar.gz
cd OOO300_m9_native_packed-1_en-US.9358
./setup
# Install into: ~/bin/install/
# Add to my path:  ~/bin/install/opt/openoffice.org3/program/soffice

# Optionally, set preferences

===========================================================================

OpenOffice 2.4.0 for Linux
[Still not installed on my laptop.]

(Individual installation, for MPI where I don't have root.)
(Otherwise:
 * use technique at http://forums.debian.net/viewtopic.php?p=139294&sid=4f3bdc19763eb061a816ef1d82df5ee9
   [That didn't work for me on my laptop; the resulting OpenOffice was crippled.]
   [To recover, I re-did the install, looked at the end of the output for
   the list of installed packages, and for each installed package did "sudo
   dpkg -r".]
 * debs are at http://download.openoffice.org/other.html#en-US, or
 * there are backports.)

# This didn't work on my laptop; the ./setup program failed.  Dunno why.
mkdir -p /scratch/mernst/oo-install
cd /scratch/mernst/oo-install
wget http://openoffice.c3sl.ufpr.br/stable/2.4.0/OOo_2.4.0_LinuxIntel_install_wJRE_en-US.tar.gz
tar -zxf OOo_2.4.0_LinuxIntel_install_wJRE_en-US.tar.gz
cd OOH680_m12_native_packed-1_en-US.9286
./setup
# Install into ~/bin/OpenOffice.org2.4
# Add its program/ directory to my path.

===========================================================================

Openoffice 2 for Debian Sarge via backports.org:

Add to /etc/apt/sources.list:
  deb http://www.backports.org/debian sarge-backports main contrib non-free

sudo apt update 
sudo apt -t sarge-backports install openoffice.org

===========================================================================

OpenOffice 1.1.1 for Linux

mkdir -p /scratch/mernst/oo-install
cd /scratch/mernst/oo-install
wget http://www.ibiblio.org/pub/mirrors/openoffice/stable/1.1.1/OOo_1.1.1_LinuxIntel_install.tar.gz
tar -zxf OOo_1.1.1_LinuxIntel_install.tar.gz
cd OOo_1.1.1_LinuxIntel_install
sudo ./setup -net
# Install into /usr/local/OpenOffice.org1.1.1
## Old:
# sudo mv /usr/local/bin/soffice /usr/local/bin/soffice-1.1.0
# sudo ln -s /usr/local/OpenOffice.org1.1.1/program/soffice /usr/local/bin/soffice-1.1.1
# (cd /usr/local/bin; sudo ln -s soffice-1.1.1 soffice)
## New:
# Edit /usr/local/bin/soffice to contain one of the following texts:

#!/bin/bash
OOFFICE_HOME=/usr/local/OpenOffice.org1.1.1/program
exec $OOFFICE_HOME/soffice "$@"

#!/bin/bash
OOFFICE_HOME=/usr/local/pkg/openoffice/openoffice-1.1.1/program
exec $OOFFICE_HOME/soffice "$@"

----------------

## Now, per-user installation.
## Note I am not root while executing the following.
/usr/local/OpenOffice.org1.1.1/setup &
# Choose "workstation installation")
# Choose ~/.OpenOffice.org1.1.1/

## The following commands may be necessary in the midst of the "setup"
## command, but otherwise do not need to be executed.
sudo chown -R mernst ~/.kde2
sudo chgrp -R mernst ~/.kde2
sudo chown mernst ~/.gnome/apps/OpenOffice.org\ 1.1.1
sudo chgrp mernst ~/.gnome/apps/OpenOffice.org\ 1.1.1
# On older machines, use ".kde" instead of ".kde2" here.
(cd ~/.kde2/share; mkdir -p icons/locolor/16x16/apps icons/locolor/32x32/apps icons/hicolor/32x32/apps icons/hicolor/48x48/apps)

